Package at.tuwien.vis2.metromaps.model.grid

Class GridGraph

java.lang.Object
at.tuwien.vis2.metromaps.model.grid.GridGraph
public class GridGraph extends Object
Wraps a graph with a fixed bounding box and an octilinear grid. It is possible to route paths on the grid graph.

  • Constructor Details

    • GridGraph

      public GridGraph(double widthInputGraph, double heightInputGraph, double[] leftUpper, double[] leftLower, double[] rightUpper, double dinput, double rinput)
      Created an octilinear grid graph with vertices of type GridVertex and edges of type GridEdge. Each vertex has 8 outgoing edges. The vertices have a distance of d. The size is calculated based on the given corner points.
      Parameters:
      widthInputGraph - width calculated in the input graph, based on most left and most right station
      heightInputGraph - height calculated in the input graph, based on most upper and most lower station
      leftUpper - coordinates of left upper grid graph boundary
      leftLower - coordinates of left lower grid graph boundary
      rightUpper - coordinates of right upper grid graph boundary
      dinput - grid distance, meaning the distance vertices have to each other in kms.
      rinput - search radius in km, stations around a radius r are considered as source/target candidates when routing a path.

  • Method Details

    • processInputEdge

      public ShortestPath processInputEdge(InputLineEdge edgeFromInputGraph, InputStation sourceFromInputGraph, InputStation targetFromInputGraph, String lineName)
      Calculates an optimal path on the grid graph from a given line of the input graph. This is always from a station to another station. Optimal means the bends are as small as possible while also the station placement is close to the original station. This method first calculates source and target candidates (edges) within a radius r of the original stations. If target or source are already routed, these stations are taken as start or end. Otherwise, offset costs are calculated for each source/target candidate edge. The closer the edge to the original station, the lower the offset cost. next, an optimal path from each source to each target candidate is calculated using dijkstra. Setting the costs of each routed edge to inf, prevents routing loops. lastly the optimal path is returned.
      Parameters:
      edgeFromInputGraph - edge that has to be routed on the grid graph
      sourceFromInputGraph - start station from input graph
      targetFromInputGraph - destination/target station from input graph.
      lineName - line that is routed currently
      Returns:
      shortest path with minimal bends and optimal station placement from input source to input destination routed on the grid graph.

    • calculateStationLabelling

      public void calculateStationLabelling(List<List<GridVertex>> allVertices, List<List<GridEdge>> allPaths)
      Proposes a position to place labels in the final octilinear output graph. This method returns the first free position (edge crossing in between stations) for station label placement.
      Parameters:
      allVertices - all routed vertices on the output graph
      allPaths - all routed edges on the output graph
